Cecily Brown, the 55-year-old British artist, has become the dominant paint=
er in a long, unbroken chain of figures who have dominated the medium=E2=80=
=94and the last in a line of those making self-conscious art that responds =
to high culture, informed by literature, philosophy, and art history. Those=
 unique talents are currently on display in a new show of her work at Paula=
 Cooper Gallery and a mid-career retrospective, Cecily Brown: Themes and Va=
riations, at the Dallas Museum of Art, which will travel to the Barnes Foun=
dation later this year, coming on the heels of her show, Death and the Maid=
, at the Met last year.

In the last seven years, Brown has also become a central figure in the art =
market. Her own market has taken a breather this year after posting a 40 pe=
rcent rise in auction volume from 2022 to 2023, when
$46 million worth of her paintings were sold. And while that amount was onl=
y good for 41st place on the list of highest-grossing artists by auction vo=
lume last year, she is far younger than the handful of other living artists=
 on the list=E2=80=94Yayoi Kusama, Jasper Johns, David Hockney, and Ed Rusc=
ha, to name a few. Her potential to keep painting is a driving force behind=
 her market value.

It=E2=80=99s not clear whether Brown=E2=80=99s recent ascent is a product o=
f her relative youth and the maturity of her market, or the fact that she h=
as retaken control of the sale and distribution of her work, slowing primar=
y sales and reconsidering placement. Whatever the cause, Brown is becoming =
a mainstay, and market-maker, to watch.

