Remixing the Masters

The challenge in curating a retrospective of Brown=E2=80=99s work is that s=
he not only paints a lot about painting=E2=80=94many of her works are exten=
ded encounters with the paintings of Old Masters=E2=80=94but also because s=
he revises and reconsiders her own work in a circular manner that defies th=
e usual chronological structure of a painter=E2=80=99s career. Dallas Museu=
m of Art curator Katherine Brodbeck highlights this theme by prominently fe=
aturing a large, four-panel work by Brown titled Saboteur Four Times, from =
2019, as the first work in her exhibition.

Brown is known to hold on to many of her paintings, often returning over ti=
me to add to a canvas or further explore an idea. But in 2019, she found a =
new strategy for this kind of recursive variation. First, she painted Sabot=
eur in her now-familiar manner=E2=80=94taking a
figurative scene and painting over it until the image becomes abstracted. (=
Oscillating between the poles of figurative fidelity and the interplay of c=
olor and form is a consistent theme in Brown=E2=80=99s work.) Then, in Sabo=
teur Four Times, she amplified that strategy by digitally reproducing Sabot=
eur on four canvases, and then painting over each image in a different way,=
 ultimately uniting the four canvases into one work.

Indeed, Brown has a habit of painting canvases separately but arranging the=
m=E2=80=94and often rearranging them=E2=80=94into singular, large-scale wor=
ks. The culmination of the show is a massive 8-by-16-foot, three-panel work=
 titled The Splendid Table, from 2019-20. Like many of the works in the sho=
w, it comes from Dallas collectors, in this case Howard Rachofsky and Thoma=
s Hartland-Mackie. But there are also works on display from other Dallas fo=
lks like Marguerite Hoffman and the Green family.

