became abstracted. Sexuality is also a central interpretive thesis for Brod=
beck=E2=80=99s exhibition. =E2=80=9CAlthough the recognizable content in he=
r work ebbs and flows,=E2=80=9D the curator writes in the catalog, =E2=80=
=9Cshe sees the groundwork laid by her early paintings as adding a sexual c=
harge that is present even as the work becomes more abstract; indeed, she d=
efines sexuality as more of an energy or tension in her work that keeps the=
 viewer engaged in the endless push and pull of her compositions.=E2=80=9D =
These themes, in turn, lead to the =E2=80=9Cinnovative use of genres and tr=
opes to dismantle the objectification of women throughout art history.=E2=
=80=9D

You can see these themes play themselves out in The 5 Senses ( https://www.=
paulacoopergallery.com/exhibitions/cecily-brown3?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+=
-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F12%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io#tab:slideshow;tab=
-1:thumbnails ), Brown=E2=80=99s show at Paula Cooper, in Chelsea, in which=
 the artist draws from allegorical paintings by Jan Brueghel the Elder and =
Peter Paul Rubens. The show also includes works on paper that elucidate Bro=
wn=E2=80=99s rarely seen fidelity in draftsmanship.

For any artist, two major museum shows in two years=E2=80=94at the Met and =
in Dallas, no less=E2=80=94is a lot. Brown=E2=80=99s last show was at the p=
restigious Louisiana Museum in Denmark in 2018. But as her institutional an=
d international recognition grows, she=E2=80=99s poised to fill a role once=
 held by an artist like Gerhard Richter: Her work is intellectually rigorou=
s and deeply engaged. It=E2=80=99s also easily recognizable. It can be appr=
eciated through color and abstraction but also, as Brodbeck is keen to demo=
nstrate, contemplated in
political, aesthetic, and art-historical terms. In that sense, Cecily Brown=
=E2=80=99s work presents the art market with a conspicuous opportunity to g=
row.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

Cecily Brown may not be an abstract painter, strictly speaking. But it is h=
ard not to see her as something of a godmother to a generation of young fem=
ale abstractionists. As luck would have it, The New Yorker released Rebecca=
 Mead=E2=80=99s profile ( https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2024/11/18/the=
-intensely-colorful-work-of-a-painter-obsessed-with-anime?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F12%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ) of Jad=
=C3=A9 Fadojutimi yesterday. The writer reveals Fadojutimi=E2=80=99s bipola=
r disorder diagnosis=E2=80=94on top of having A.D.H.D. and possibly synesth=
esia=E2=80=94and recent institutionalization. As Fadojutimi notes to
Mead:

* =E2=80=9CWhat was shocking to me was how scary it can be to be told that =
you have got to live with loads of people that are unwell, and you are sayi=
ng you are not unwell, and they are also saying they are not unwell=E2=80=
=94but they really are, and you really are.=E2=80=9D

Fadojutimi=E2=80=99s art can hardly be reduced to her mental health challen=
ges, as the profile makes clear. Read it=E2=80=94and let me know what you t=
hink.

Let=E2=80=99s talk more on Sunday,
