x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><i>But first=E2=80=
=A6</i><br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-he=
ight:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-f=
ormat:bullet"><li><i>Frank Auerbach dies at 93</i>: It was revealed this mo=
rning that <b>Frank Auerbach</b>, who arrived in London as part of a refuge=
e program for German Jewish children during World War II (his parents were =
killed in Auschwitz in 1942), has died. Known for his heavily impastoed can=
vases, Auerbach was a contemporary of <b>Francis</b> <b>Bacon</b> and <b>Lu=
cian</b> <b>Freud</b>, who owned an extensive amount of Auerbach=E2=80=99s =
work. <b>David</b> <b>Bowie</b> was also a fan; he owned Auerbach=E2=80=99s=
 <i>Head of Gerda Boehm</i>, which Sotheby=E2=80=99s sold for =C2=A33.8 mil=
lion in 2016 in an auction of the late musician=E2=80=99s art collection. T=
his fall, <b>Francis Outred</b> and Offer Waterman
mounted an important <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9p=
ZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUSXUxMW5uTDdMbm14N1g4Y19BST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cud2F0ZXJtYW4uY28udWsvZXhoaWJpdGlvbnMvOTUtZnJhbmstYXVlcmJhY2gtcG=
9ydHJhaXRzLW9mLWxvbmRvbi1wcmVzZW50ZWQtYnktb2ZmZXItd2F0ZXJtYW4tZnJhbmNpcy1vd=
XRyZWQvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTElMkYxMiUy=
RjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pbyIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTd=
kYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MTk3MzY3M30/245227cb878874e143c671cda754907d35=
a8eb8f8f1ff1ce064015d2f90ebbb8" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none=
;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">survey</a></u> of Auerbach=E2=80=99s Londo=
n landscapes. </li><br/><li><i>Warhol=E2=80=99s Farrah Fawcett portrait is =
finally being sold</i>: The late actor <b>Ryan O=E2=80=99Neal</b> loved <b>=
Andy</b> <b>Warhol</b>=E2=80=99s portrait of <b>Farrah Fawcett </b>so much =
that he stole it back from her, won a jury trial to retain possession of it=
, and then tried to sell it for <i>$20 million</i>. This month, the piece <=
u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uk=
txclJLZ0dUSXUxMW5uTDdMbm14N1g4Y19BST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm9uaGFtc=
y5jb20vYXVjdGlvbi8yOTUyMS9sb3QvMTJBL2FuZHktd2FyaG9sLTE5MjgtMTk4Ny1mYXJyYWgt=
ZmF3Y2V0dC00MC14LTQwLWluLTEwMTYteC0xMDE2LWNtLXBhaW50ZWQtaW4tMTk4MC8_dXRtX2N=
hbXBhaWduPVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMSUyRjEyJTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMj=
Z1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiL=
CJsaW5rX2lkIjoxOTczNjc0fQ/d4bd7ea396ed75ff0097294793b2f78f61022c86de0e1cb80=
f820035bafad75c" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bo=
ld" class=3D"sdf">will be auctioned</a></u> at Bonhams with an estimate of =
$300,000. <br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s not much of a secret that O=E2=80=99Neal, =
who died at 82 last year, was a jerk to Fawcett over the course of their re=
lationship. When Fawcett, who had been the subject of one of the bestsellin=
g posters of all time, died in 2009, O=E2=80=99Neal went to her house and t=
ook one of the two portraits Warhol made of Farrah, claiming that the paint=
ing was only at her house for safekeeping. In her will, she left at least o=
ne of her two Warhols to the University of Texas=E2=80=99s Blanton Museum. =
It took <i>years</i> and a jury trial for O=E2=80=99Neal to gain legal titl=
e to the artwork. In 2019, the <i>New York Post</i> claimed O=E2=80=99Neal =
was trying to sell the
painting for that $20 million sum, presumably because it was a Warhol. <br/=
><br/>Some of the celebrity portraits Warhol made in the =E2=80=9970s and =
=E2=80=9980s have become quite valuable, but that number was profoundly unr=
ealistic. A <b>Muhammad Ali</b>, from 1977, sold for $10 million in 2019 an=
d $18 million in 2021. Versions of <b>Brigitte Bardot</b>, from 1974, sold =
for $11.6 million and $10.5 million in 2014 and 2007, respectively. A <b>De=
bbie Harry</b>, from 1980, made $7.9 million last year, and $3 million in 2=
014. <b>Princess Diana</b>, from 1982, just made $3 million in London in Ma=
rch. And a <b>John Lennon</b>, from 1985, made $2.8 million 10 years ago. W=
hat does that make Farrah Fawcett worth? I dunno. But this one should be in=
teresting to watch. </li><br/><li><i>Sotheby=E2=80=99s delayed Hong Kong sa=
le struggles</i>: The Hong Kong market is in hibernation, which has been in=
convenient, to say the least, for the auction houses launching their new ou=
tposts in the autonomous region.
Sotheby=E2=80=99s had trouble gathering property for its debut sale, origin=
ally scheduled for September, so they had to regroup and hold the sales thi=
s week. The <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnV=
DJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUSXUxMW5uTDdMbm14N1g4Y19BST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc2NtcC5jb20vbGlmZXN0eWxlL2FydHMtY3VsdHVyZS9hcnRpY2xlLzMyODYxMTUvbWFyay1=
yb3Roa28tcGFpbnRpbmctc2VsbHMtMzAtbGVzcy0yMDE1LXNob3dpbmctaG9uZy1rb25nLW1hcm=
tldC1jaGFsbGVuZ2VzP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4M=
TElMkYxMiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pbyIsImludGVybmFsIjoi=
ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MTk3MzY3NX0/aade7e0a307a9899bda0770=
1b246fd63d8c15d0f1e717950f90e7b0f10984088" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-deco=
ration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">evening sale</a></u> made HK$40=
9 million ($52 million), with seven lots withdrawn and five lots unsold. Ev=
en in a tough sale, however, there were strong performances for works by <b=
>Maria Kreyn</b>, <b>Shi Hu</b>, and <b>Zenzaburo Kojima</b>.<br/><br/>Amon=
g the bigger sales was a giant blue-and-yellow <b>Rothko</b> that had once =
been owned, in turn, by <b>Bunny Mellon</b> and <b>Fran=C3=A7ois Pinault</b=
>,
which is a gold-standard provenance. <i>Then </i>it went to fugitive Malays=
ian financier <b>Jho Low</b>. After that, it was auctioned in 2015, for $46=
 million, to Azerbaijani oligarch <b>Farkhad Akhmedov</b>, whose wife, <b>T=
atiana</b>, would later receive cash and art valued at $186 million in a di=
vorce settlement. On Monday, the painting was acquired by art advisor <b>Pa=
tti Wong</b> for HK$252.5 million ($32.5 million), which was probably the i=
rrevocable bid. </li><br/><li><i>Sotheby=E2=80=99s enhanced hammer whispers=
</i>: The fallow Asian market was one reason that Sotheby=E2=80=99s struggl=
ed to gather property for its Hong Kong sales. Another may have been the ne=
w fee structure that the auction house put in place after the May sales, in=
 which Sotheby=E2=80=99s lowered the buyer=E2=80=99s premium but revived a =
vendor=E2=80=99s commission, and instituted a strict policy of forbidding e=
nhanced hammer deals. The ban on enhanced hammer deals made it difficult fo=
r the house=E2=80=99s specialists to do what they
do best=E2=80=94namely, identify the artists whose work is most in demand a=
nd secure lots by them.<br/><br/>Without sweeteners for lots that fell belo=
w the threshold for modifying fees or weren=E2=80=99t brought to market wit=
h guarantees, the Sotheby=E2=80=99s team was playing with one hand tied beh=
ind its back. All fall, we=E2=80=99ve seen anemic sale totals in London and=
 Hong Kong. Paris dispensed with its day sale. Would New York be the same s=
tory? With big-ticket collections on offer, like <b>Sydell</b> <b>Miller</b=
>=E2=80=99s, it=E2=80=99s hard to tell where Sotheby=E2=80=99s stands with =
this new incentive plan. But the best way to measure the firm=E2=80=99s abi=
lity to land consignments is by looking at the November day sales of contem=
porary art. There, we have the surprise of the season: Sotheby=E2=80=99s ag=
gregate estimate for the contemporary day sale is $56.7 million; Christie=
=E2=80=99s is $55.2 million. Sotheby=E2=80=99s was able to post that number=
 by landing 313 consignments at an average estimate of $181,000. Christie=
=E2=80=99s came
in at 230 lots averaging $240,000. Something changed between Paris and New =
York. Was enhanced hammer really not a hurdle to consignors?<br/><br/>I=E2=
=80=99ve heard reports from art advisors that Sotheby=E2=80=99s may be tryi=
ng to finesse its own rules by giving bespoke terms to advisors whose aggre=
gate business with Sotheby=E2=80=99s meets a certain threshold. Other advis=
ors tell me they=E2=80=99ve seen deal sheets that contradict the new policy=
=2E But that=E2=80=99s just gossip, perhap=
s to be expected with art advisors=20=
spitting tacks over Sotheby=E2=80=99s new policy. So believe that at your o=
wn risk. It would not be surprising to hear that Sotheby=E2=80=99s is bendi=
ng its own rules to make sure the all-important November sales don=E2=80=99=
t look weak. In fact, that would be a smart move; however, time will tell w=
hether this is the beginning of a quiet retreat in the battle of the enhanc=
ed hammer. <br/></li></ul></td>
