         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s1">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b>Cecily Brown</b>=
, the 55-year-old British artist, has become the dominant painter in a long=
, unbroken chain of figures who have dominated the medium=E2=80=94and the <=
i>last</i> in a line of those making self-conscious art that responds to hi=
gh culture, informed by literature, philosophy, and art history. Those uniq=
ue talents are currently on display in a new show of her work at Paula Coop=
er Gallery and a mid-career retrospective, <i>Cecily Brown: Themes and Vari=
ations</i>, at the Dallas Museum of Art, which will travel to the Barnes Fo=
undation later this year, coming on the heels of her show, <i>Death and the=
 Maid</i>, at the Met last year. <br/><br/>In the last seven years, Brown h=
as also become a central figure in the art market. Her own market has taken=
 a breather this year after posting a 40 percent rise in auction volume fro=
m 2022 to 2023, when
$46 million worth of her paintings were sold. And while that amount was onl=
y good for 41st place on the list of highest-grossing artists by auction vo=
lume last year, she is far younger than the handful of other living artists=
 on the list=E2=80=94<b>Yayoi Kusama</b>, <b>Jasper Johns</b>, <b>David Hoc=
kney</b>, and <b>Ed Ruscha</b>, to name a few. Her potential to keep painti=
ng is a driving force behind her market value.<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s not cl=
ear whether Brown=E2=80=99s recent ascent is a product of her relative yout=
h and the maturity of her market, <i>or</i> the fact that she has retaken c=
ontrol of the sale and distribution of her work, slowing primary sales and =
reconsidering placement. Whatever the cause, Brown is becoming a mainstay, =
and market-maker, to watch. <br/></td>
         </tr>
