          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The challenge in cu=
rating a retrospective of Brown=E2=80=99s work is that she not only paints =
a lot about <i>painting=E2=80=94</i>many of her works are extended encounte=
rs with the paintings of Old Masters=E2=80=94but also because she revises a=
nd reconsiders her own work in a circular manner that defies the usual chro=
nological structure of a painter=E2=80=99s career. Dallas Museum of Art cur=
ator <b>Katherine</b> <b>Brodbeck</b> highlights this theme by prominently =
featuring a large, four-panel work by Brown titled <i>Saboteur Four Times</=
i>, from 2019, as the first work in her exhibition. <br/><br/>Brown is know=
n to hold on to many of her paintings, often returning over time to add to =
a canvas or further explore an idea. But in 2019, she found a new strategy =
for this kind of recursive variation. First, she painted <i>Saboteur</i> in=
 her now-familiar manner=E2=80=94taking a
figurative scene and painting over it until the image becomes abstracted. (=
Oscillating between the poles of figurative fidelity and the interplay of c=
olor and form is a consistent theme in Brown=E2=80=99s work.) Then, in <i>S=
aboteur Four Times</i>, she amplified that strategy by digitally reproducin=
g <i>Saboteur</i> on four canvases, and then painting over each image in a =
different way, ultimately uniting the four canvases into one work.<br/><br/=
>Indeed, Brown has a habit of painting canvases separately but arranging th=
em=E2=80=94and often rearranging them=E2=80=94into singular, large-scale wo=
rks. The culmination of the show is a massive 8-by-16-foot, three-panel wor=
k titled <i>The Splendid Table</i>, from 2019-20. Like many of the works in=
 the show, it comes from Dallas collectors, in this case <b>Howard Rachofsk=
y</b> and <b>Thomas Hartland-Mackie</b>. But there are also works on displa=
y from other Dallas folks like <b>Marguerite Hoffman</b> and the <b>Green</=
b> family. </td>
         </tr>
