          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">According to Brodbe=
ck=E2=80=99s thesis, <i>Saboteur Four Times</i> deserves to be one of the l=
ast works in the Dallas retrospective, even if the visitor sees it first, b=
ecause it points =E2=80=9Cforward to new avenues in the artist=E2=80=99s pr=
oduction.=E2=80=9D The 30 large-scale paintings in the show look backward b=
y dividing Brown=E2=80=99s work into four themes. In addition to revision, =
the themes include scenes of figures in landscape settings, drawing from th=
e work of <b>Francisco de Goya</b>, <b>Tintoretto</b>, and <b>Fragonard</b>=
; images of shipwrecks and sirens referencing <b>G=C3=A9ricault</b>; and, f=
inally, the artist=E2=80=99s own handling of nudes.<br/><br/>That last one =
isn=E2=80=99t just a gesture toward the standard artistic exercise of paint=
ing flesh. Eroticism is a wellspring for Brown=E2=80=99s art: Many of her e=
arly paintings began as graphic depictions of sex, even if they
became abstracted. Sexuality is also a central interpretive thesis for Brod=
beck=E2=80=99s exhibition. =E2=80=9CAlthough the recognizable content in he=
r work ebbs and flows,=E2=80=9D the curator writes in the catalog, =E2=80=
=9Cshe sees the groundwork laid by her early paintings as adding a sexual c=
harge that is present even as the work becomes more abstract; indeed, she d=
efines sexuality as more of an energy or tension in her work that keeps the=
 viewer engaged in the endless push and pull of her compositions.=E2=80=9D =
These themes, in turn, lead to the =E2=80=9Cinnovative use of genres and tr=
opes to dismantle the objectification of women throughout art history.=E2=
=80=9D<br/><br/>You can see these themes play themselves out in <i><u><a hr=
ef=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ=
0dUSXUxMW5uTDdMbm14N1g4Y19BST0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucGF1bGFjb29wZXJn=
YWxsZXJ5LmNvbS9leGhpYml0aW9ucy9jZWNpbHktYnJvd24zP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1XYWxsK1B=
vd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MTElMkYxMiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdX=
N0b21lci5pbyN0YWI6c2xpZGVzaG93O3RhYi0xOnRodW1ibmFpbHMiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2Y=
zYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjE5NzMyNzB9/3bb6807efcc9e824963625927d8=
886de8b76643e59b204891e0adbc7774e3a7a" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decorati=
on:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">The 5 Senses</a></u></i>, Brown=E2=
=80=99s show at Paula Cooper, in Chelsea, in which the artist draws from al=
legorical paintings by <b>Jan Brueghel the Elder</b> and <b>Peter Paul Rube=
ns</b>. The show also includes works on paper that elucidate Brown=E2=80=99=
s rarely seen fidelity in draftsmanship. <br/><br/>For any artist, two majo=
r museum shows in two years=E2=80=94at the Met and in Dallas, no less=E2=80=
=94is a <i>lot</i>. Brown=E2=80=99s last show was at the prestigious Louisi=
ana Museum in Denmark in 2018. But as her institutional and international r=
ecognition grows, she=E2=80=99s poised to fill a role once held by an artis=
t like <b>Gerhard</b> <b>Richter</b>: Her work is intellectually rigorous a=
nd deeply engaged. It=E2=80=99s also easily recognizable. It can be appreci=
ated through color and abstraction but also, as Brodbeck is keen to demonst=
rate, contemplated in
political, aesthetic, and art-historical terms. In that sense, Cecily Brown=
=E2=80=99s work presents the art market with a conspicuous opportunity to g=
row. <br/></td>
         </tr>
